  "prompt": "How do you do \"inline if\" in JavaScript?",
  "response": "In JavaScript, there are several ways to do an \"inline if\" or conditional (ternary) expression:\n\n1. Ternary Operator (Most Common):\n```javascript\ncondition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse\n\n// Example:\nlet age = 20;\nlet canVote = age >= 18 ? \"Yes\" : \"No\";\n\n// Another example\nlet message = isLoggedIn ? \"Welcome\" : \"Please log in\";\n```\n\n2. Logical AND (&&) Shorthand:\n```javascript\n// This works for conditionally rendering or executing\ncondition && expressionIfTrue\n\n// Example:\nisAdmin && showAdminPanel();\n\n// Another example\nlet name = user && user.name;\n```\n\n3. Logical OR (||) for Default Values:\n```javascript\nlet name = inputName || \"Anonymous\";\n```\n\n4. Nested Ternary (use sparingly):\n```javascript\nlet result = condition1 ? value1 \n           : condition2 ? value2 \n           : condition3 ? value3 \n           : defaultValue;\n```\n\n5. Optional Chaining (?.) (ES2020):\n```javascript\nlet userName = user?.name;  // Returns undefined if user is null/undefined\n```\n\nEach method has its use cases:\n- Ternary is best for simple conditional assignments\n- && is good for conditional rendering or execution\n- || is great for default values\n- Optional chaining helps with nested property access\n\nExample with multiple use cases:\n```javascript\n// Ternary for assignment\nlet status = score > 70 ? \"Pass\" : \"Fail\";\n\n// && for conditional rendering\nisLoggedIn && <WelcomeMessage />\n\n// || for default value\nfunction greet(name) {\n  console.log(`Hello, ${name || \"Guest\"}!`);\n}\n```",
